\cf0 `\\newthought\{During this dark period of persecution,\}`\{=latex\} advocates for homosexuals (at this time called 'homophile' organizations) focused primarily on changing the stereotypes of the homosexual as a step towards ending the criminalization of homosexual acts as well as the psychological and medical 'treatments.'  There was little activity within the scientific and academic communities on the issue. \
\
That all started to change when a young social psychologist named `\\index[gamebook]\{Hooker, Evelyn\}`\{=latex\}Evelyn Hooker started teaching at UCLA.
\f0 \

\f2 \
During WWII, young men and women who were accused of homosexuality in Pacific theater of operations tended to be discharged from the military in California ports, including San Diego, Long Beach and San Francisco. Many, if not most, of these young people could not return to their hometowns because of their dishonorable discharge from the military. As a result, a organic community of homosexuals began taking shape in many of these cities.
\f0 \

\f2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li283\fi-283\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 Hooker became friends with one of her UCLA graduate students, Sam Fromm. Sam was gay. In 1943, he challenged her to study 'people like him' to determine if they were mentally ill (specifically 'neurotic') independently of the biases against homosexuality inherent in the psychiatric {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://2373462F-96CE-40A1-BFC9-398F6277061B"}}{\fldrslt tradition.}} In a 1998 interview, Hooker explained the significance of this phrase:
\f0\fs24 \

\f2\fs20 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li283\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0  > \'93This bright young man, somewhere in his early thirties, had obviously been thinking about this for a long time. And by \'91people like us\'92 he meant, \'91We\'92re homosexual, but we don\'92t need psychiatrists. We don\'92t need psychologists. We\'92re not insane. We\'92re not any of those things they say we are.\'94 (Eric Marcus, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivlnk://82339BBA-0C32-452F-980A-044FFC0D58FE"}}{\fldrslt Windy City Times}}, October 31, 2007 \'95 vol 23 no 07)
\f0 \

\f2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 During the 1940s, Evelyn Hooker became a trusted 'outsider' of the gay community in L.A., but didn't want to conduct research on people she saw as her friends.
\f0 \

\f2 \
